        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Bromley, | Kent. S.E.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Mar 16</date>
                    <salute>Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am much obliged for your letter of Mar 10<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>.</p>
<p>I am pleased to hear that you have been interested in my work on the Origin of Species. Your law of inheritance I dare say is true &amp; may have some bearing on the modification of species; but I fear it would be difficult to prove it with sufficient clearness to allow of its use<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I beg to remain | Dear Sir | Yours respectfully | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">An incomplete version of this letter, dated 15 March [1865] and lacking the first sentence and the valediction, was published in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 13, based on a transcription in a Stargardt sale catalogue. This transcription is from a facsimile in a Christie’s sale catalogue. The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4783.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Rudolph Heine, 10 March 1865</ref> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 13).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4783.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Rudolph Heine, 10 March 1865</ref> and n. 2 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 13).</note>
